[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] In computing, **aspect-oriented programming** (**AOP**) is a programming paradigm that aims to increase modularity by allowing the separation of *cross-cutting concerns*.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] It does so by adding behavior to existing code (an advice) *without* modifying the code, instead separately specifying which code is modified via a "pointcut" specification, such as "log all function calls when the function's name begins with 'set'".
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] This allows behaviors that are not central to the business logic (such as logging) to be added to a program without cluttering the code of core functions.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] AOP includes programming methods and tools that support the modularization of concerns at the level of the source code, while **aspect-oriented software development** refers to a whole engineering discipline.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Aspect-oriented programming entails breaking down program logic into cohesive areas of functionality (so-called *concerns*).
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Nearly all programming paradigms support some level of grouping and encapsulation of concerns into separate, independent entities by providing abstractions (e.g., functions, procedures, modules, classes, methods) that can be used for implementing, abstracting, and composing these concerns.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Some concerns "cut across" multiple abstractions in a program, and defy these forms of implementation.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] These concerns are called *cross-cutting concerns* or horizontal concerns.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Logging exemplifies a cross-cutting concern because a logging strategy must affect every logged part of the system.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Logging thereby *crosscuts* all logged classes and methods.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] All AOP implementations have some cross-cutting expressions that encapsulate each concern in one place.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The difference between implementations lies in the power, safety, and usability of the constructs provided.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, interceptors that specify the methods to express a limited form of cross-cutting, without much support for type-safety or debugging.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] AspectJ has a number of such expressions and encapsulates them in a special class, called an aspect.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, an aspect can alter the behavior of the base code (the non-aspect part of a program) by applying advice (additional behavior) at various join points (points in a program) specified in a quantification or query called a pointcut (that detects whether a given join point matches).
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] An aspect can also make binary-compatible structural changes to other classes, such as adding members or parents.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] AOP has several direct antecedents: reflection and metaobject protocols, subject-oriented programming, Composition Filters, and Adaptive Programming.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Gregor Kiczales and colleagues at Xerox PARC developed the explicit concept of AOP and followed this with the AspectJ AOP extension to Java.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] IBM's research team pursued a tool approach over a language design approach and in 2001 proposed Hyper/J and the Concern Manipulation Environment, which have not seen wide use.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The examples in this article use AspectJ.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The Microsoft Transaction Server is considered to be the first major application of AOP followed by Enterprise JavaBeans.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Typically, an aspect is *scattered* or *tangled* as code, making it harder to understand and maintain.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] It is scattered by the function (such as logging) being spread over a number of unrelated functions that might use *its* function, possibly in entirely unrelated systems or written in different languages.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Thus, changing logging can require modifying all affected modules.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Aspects become tangled not only with the mainline function of the systems in which they are expressed but also with each other.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Changing one concern thus entails understanding all the tangled concerns or having some means by which the effect of changes can be inferred.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, consider a banking application with a conceptually very simple method for transferring an amount from one account to another.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] In this example, other interests have become *tangled* with the basic functionality (sometimes called the *business logic concern*).
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Transactions, security, and logging all exemplify *cross-cutting concerns*.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Now consider what would happen if we suddenly need to change the security considerations for the application.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] In the program's current version, security-related operations appear *scattered* across numerous methods, and such a change would require major effort.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] AOP tries to solve this problem by allowing the programmer to express cross-cutting concerns in stand-alone modules called *aspects*.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Aspects can contain *advice* (code joined to specified points in the program) and *inter-type declarations* (structural members added to other classes).
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, a security module can include advice that performs a security check before accessing a bank account.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The pointcut defines the times (join points) when one can access a bank account, and the code in the advice body defines how the security check is implemented.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] That way, both the check and the places can be maintained in one place.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Further, a good pointcut can anticipate later program changes, so if another developer creates a new method to access the bank account, the advice will apply to the new method when it executes.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] One can think of AOP as a debugging tool or a user-level tool.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Advice should be reserved for cases in which one cannot get the function changed (user level) or do not want to change the function in production code (debugging).
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The advice-related component of an aspect-oriented language defines a join point model (JPM).
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] A way to specify (or *quantify*) join points, called *pointcuts*.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Pointcuts determine whether a given join point matches.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Most useful pointcut languages use a syntax like the base language (for example, AspectJ uses Java signatures) and allow reuse through naming and combination.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] A means of specifying code to run at a join point.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] AspectJ calls this *advice*, and can run it before, after, and around join points.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Some implementations also support defining a method in an aspect on another class.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Join-point models can be compared based on the join points exposed, how join points are specified, the operations permitted at the join points, and the structural enhancements that can be expressed.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] All advice languages can be defined in terms of their JPM.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] This code snippet adds the `acceptVisitor` method to the `Point` class.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Any structural additions are required to be compatible with the original class, so that clients of the existing class continue to operate, unless the AOP implementation can expect to control all clients at all times.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] 2. the ultimate interpreter or environment is updated to understand and implement AOP features.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The difficulty of changing environments means most implementations produce compatible combination programs through a type of program transformation known as *weaving*.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] An aspect weaver reads the aspect-oriented code and generates appropriate object-oriented code with the aspects integrated.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The same AOP language can be implemented through a variety of weaving methods, so the semantics of a language should never be understood in terms of the weaving implementation.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Only the speed of an implementation and its ease of deployment are affected by the method of combination used.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Systems can implement source-level weaving using preprocessors (as C++ was implemented originally in CFront) that require access to program source files.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] However, Java's well-defined binary form enables bytecode weavers to work with any Java program in .class-file form.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Bytecode weavers can be deployed during the build process or, if the weave model is per-class, during class loading.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] AspectJ started with source-level weaving in 2001, delivered a per-class bytecode weaver in 2002, and offered advanced load-time support after the integration of AspectWerkz in 2005.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Any solution that combines programs at runtime must provide views that segregate them properly to maintain the programmer's segregated model.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Java's bytecode support for multiple source files enables any debugger to step through a properly woven .class file in a source editor.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] However, some third-party decompilers cannot process woven code because they expect code produced by Javac rather than all supported bytecode forms (see also § Criticism, below).
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Deploy-time weaving offers another approach.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] This basically implies post-processing, but rather than patching the generated code, this weaving approach *subclasses* existing classes so that the modifications are introduced by method-overriding.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The existing classes remain untouched, even at runtime, and all existing tools, such as debuggers and profilers, can be used during development.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] A similar approach has already proven itself in the implementation of many Java EE application servers, such as IBM's WebSphere.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Even though most classes in an object-oriented model will perform a single, specific function, they often share common, secondary requirements with other classes.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, we may want to add logging to classes within the data-access layer and also to classes in the UI layer whenever a thread enters or exits a method.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Even though each class has a very different primary functionality, the code needed to perform the secondary functionality is often identical.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] This is the additional code that you want to apply to your existing model.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] This refers to the point of execution in the application at which cross-cutting concern needs to be applied.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] In our example, a pointcut is reached when the thread enters a method, and another pointcut is reached when the thread exits the method.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The combination of the pointcut and the advice is termed an aspect.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] In the example above, we add a logging aspect to our application by defining a pointcut and giving the correct advice.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Aspects emerged from object-oriented programming and reflective programming.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] AOP languages have functionality similar to, but more restricted than, metaobject protocols.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Aspects relate closely to programming concepts like subjects, mixins, and delegation.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Other ways to use aspect-oriented programming paradigms include Composition Filters and the hyperslices approach.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Since at least the 1970s, developers have been using forms of interception and dispatch-patching that resemble some of the implementation methods for AOP, but these never had the semantics that the cross-cutting specifications provide in one place.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Designers have considered alternative ways to achieve separation of code, such as C#'s partial types, but such approaches lack a quantification mechanism that allows reaching several join points of the code with one declarative statement.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Though it may seem unrelated, in testing, the use of mocks or stubs requires the use of AOP techniques, such as around advice.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Here the collaborating objects are for the purpose of the test, a cross-cutting concern.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Thus, the various Mock Object frameworks provide these features.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, a process invokes a service to get a balance amount.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] In the test of the process, it is unimportant where the amount comes from, but only that the process uses the balance according to the requirements.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Programmers need to be able to read and understand code to prevent errors.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Even with proper education, understanding cross-cutting concerns can be difficult without proper support for visualizing both static structure and the dynamic flow of a program.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Starting in 2002, AspectJ began to provide IDE plug-ins to support the visualizing of cross-cutting concerns.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Those features, as well as aspect code assist and refactoring, are now common.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Given the power of AOP, making a logical mistake in expressing cross-cutting can lead to widespread program failure.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Conversely, another programmer may change the join points in a program, such as by renaming or moving methods, in ways that the aspect writer did not anticipate and with unforeseen consequences.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] One advantage of modularizing cross-cutting concerns is enabling one programmer to easily affect the entire system.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] As a result, such problems manifest as a conflict over responsibility between two or more developers for a given failure.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] AOP can expedite solving these problems, as only the aspect must be changed.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Without AOP, the corresponding problems can be much more spread out.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The most basic criticism of the effect of AOP is that control flow is obscured, and that it is not only worse than the much-maligned GOTO statement, but is closely analogous to the joke COME FROM statement.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The *obliviousness of application*, which is fundamental to many definitions of AOP (the code in question has no indication that an advice will be applied, which is specified instead in the pointcut), means that the advice is not visible, in contrast to an explicit method call.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Indeed, the pointcut may depend on runtime condition and thus not be statically deterministic.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] This can be mitigated but not solved by static analysis and IDE support showing which advices *potentially* match.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] General criticisms are that AOP purports to improve "both modularity and the structure of code", but some counter that it instead undermines these goals and impedes "independent development and understandability of programs".
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Cross-cutting concerns potentially cross-cut each other, requiring some resolution mechanism, such as ordering.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Indeed, aspects can apply to themselves, leading to problems such as the liar paradox.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] Technical criticisms include that the quantification of pointcuts (defining where advices are executed) is "extremely sensitive to changes in the program", which is known as the *fragile pointcut problem*.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] The problems with pointcuts are deemed intractable.
[src:spring-framework-lib/aspect-oriented-programming] If one replaces the quantification of pointcuts with explicit annotations, one obtains attribute-oriented programming instead, which is simply an explicit subroutine call and suffers the identical problem of scattering, which AOP was designed to solve.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] In software engineering, **dependency injection** is a programming technique in which an object or function receives other objects or functions that it requires, as opposed to creating them internally.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Dependency injection aims to separate the concerns of constructing objects and using them, leading to loosely coupled programs.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The pattern ensures that an object or function that wants to use a given service should not have to know how to construct those services.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Instead, the receiving "client" (object or function) is provided with its dependencies by external code (an "injector"), which it is not aware of.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Dependency injection is often used to keep code in-line with the dependency inversion principle.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] In statically typed languages using dependency injection means that a client only needs to declare the interfaces of the services it uses, rather than their concrete implementations, making it easier to change which services are used at runtime without recompiling.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Application frameworks often combine dependency injection with inversion of control.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Under inversion of control, the framework first constructs an object (such as a controller), and then passes control flow to it.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] With dependency injection, the framework also instantiates the dependencies declared by the application object (often in the constructor method's parameters), and passes the dependencies into the object.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Dependency injection implements the idea of "inverting control over the implementations of dependencies", which is why certain Java frameworks generically name the concept "inversion of control" (not to be confused with inversion of control flow).
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Dependency injection involves four roles: services, clients, interfaces, and injectors.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] A service is any class which contains useful functionality.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] In turn, a client is any class which uses services.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The services that a client requires are the client's *dependencies*.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Any object can be a service or a client; the names relate only to the role the objects play in an injection.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The same object may even be both a client (it uses injected services) and a service (it is injected into other objects).
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Upon injection, the service is made part of the client's state, available for use.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Clients should not know how their dependencies are implemented, only their names and API.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] A service which retrieves emails, for instance, may use the IMAP or POP3 protocols behind the scenes, but this detail is likely irrelevant to calling code that merely wants an email retrieved.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] By ignoring implementation details, clients do not need to change when their dependencies do.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The **injector**, sometimes also called an assembler, container, provider or factory, introduces services to the client.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The role of injectors is to construct and connect complex object graphs, where objects may be both clients and services.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The injector itself may be many objects working together, but must not be the client, as this would create a circular dependency.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Because dependency injection separates how objects are constructed from how they are used, it often diminishes the importance of the **`new`** keyword found in most object-oriented languages.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Because the framework handles creating services, the programmer tends to only directly construct value objects which represents entities in the program's domain (such as an `Employee` object in a business app or an `Order` object in a shopping app).
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] As an analogy, cars can be thought of as services which perform the useful work of transporting people from one place to another.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Car engines can require gas, diesel or electricity, but this detail is unimportant to the client—a passenger—who only cares if it can get them to their destination.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Cars present a uniform interface through their pedals, steering wheels and other controls.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] As such, which engine they were 'injected' with on the factory line ceases to matter and drivers can switch between any kind of car as needed.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] A basic benefit of dependency injection is decreased coupling between classes and their dependencies.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] By removing a client's knowledge of how its dependencies are implemented, programs become more reusable, testable and maintainable.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] This also results in increased flexibility: a client may act on anything that supports the intrinsic interface the client expects.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] More generally, dependency injection reduces boilerplate code, since all dependency creation is handled by a singular component.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Finally, dependency injection allows concurrent development.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Two developers can independently develop classes that use each other, while only needing to know the interface the classes will communicate through.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Plugins are often developed by third-parties that never even talk to developers of the original product.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Many of dependency injection's benefits are particularly relevant to unit-testing.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] For example, dependency injection can be used to externalize a system's configuration details into configuration files, allowing the system to be reconfigured without recompilation.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Separate configurations can be written for different situations that require different implementations of components.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Similarly, because dependency injection does not require any change in code behavior, it can be applied to legacy code as a refactoring.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] This makes clients more independent and are easier to unit test in isolation, using stubs or mock objects, that simulate other objects not under test.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] This ease of testing is often the first benefit noticed when using dependency injection.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] In some frameworks, clients do not need to actively accept dependency injection at all.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] In Java, for example, reflection can make private attributes public when testing and inject services directly.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] In the following Java example, the `Client` class contains a `Service` member variable initialized in the constructor.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The client directly constructs and controls which service it uses, creating a hard-coded dependency.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The most common form of dependency injection is for a class to request its dependencies through its constructor.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] This ensures the client is always in a valid state, since it cannot be instantiated without its necessary dependencies.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Dependencies are passed as arguments to a specific method, allowing them to be used only during that method's execution without maintaining a long-term reference.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] This approach is particularly useful for temporary dependencies or when different implementations are needed for various method calls.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] By accepting dependencies through a setter method, rather than a constructor, clients can allow injectors to manipulate their dependencies at any time.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] This offers flexibility, but makes it difficult to ensure that all dependencies are injected and valid before the client is used.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] With interface injection, dependencies are completely ignorant of their clients, yet still send and receive references to new clients.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] In this way, the dependencies become injectors.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The key is that the injecting method is provided through an interface.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] An assembler is still needed to introduce the client and its dependencies.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The assembler takes a reference to the client, casts it to the setter interface that sets that dependency, and passes it to that dependency object which in turn passes a reference to itself back to the client.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] For interface injection to have value, the dependency must do something in addition to simply passing back a reference to itself.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] This could be acting as a factory or sub-assembler to resolve other dependencies, thus abstracting some details from the main assembler.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] It could be reference-counting so that the dependency knows how many clients are using it.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] If the dependency maintains a collection of clients, it could later inject them all with a different instance of itself.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] The simplest way of implementing dependency injection is to manually arrange services and clients, typically done at the program's root, where execution begins.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Manual construction may be more complex and involve builders, factories, or other construction patterns.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Manual dependency injection is often tedious and error-prone for larger projects, promoting the use of frameworks which automate the process.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Manual dependency injection becomes a dependency injection framework once the constructing code is no longer custom to the application and is instead universal.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] While useful, these tools are not required in order to perform dependency injection.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] Even with a potentially long and complex object graph, the only class mentioned in code is the entry point, in this case `Client`.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] `Client` has not undergone any changes to work with Spring and remains a POJO.
[src:spring-framework-lib/dependency-injection] By keeping Spring-specific annotations and calls from spreading out among many classes, the system stays only loosely dependent on Spring.
