[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Enterprise application integration is an integration framework composed of a collection of technologies and services which form a middleware or "middleware framework" to enable integration of systems and applications across an enterprise.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Many types of business software such as supply chain management applications, ERP systems, CRM applications for managing customers, business intelligence applications, payroll, and human resources systems typically cannot communicate with one another in order to share data or business rules.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] For this reason, such applications are sometimes referred to as islands of automation or information silos.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] This lack of communication leads to inefficiencies, wherein identical data are stored in multiple locations, or straightforward processes are unable to be automated.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Applications can be linked either at the back-end via APIs or (seldom) the front-end (GUI).
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] The various systems that need to be linked together may reside on different operating systems, use different database solutions or computer languages, or different date and time formats, or could be legacy systems that are no longer supported by the vendor who originally created them.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] In some cases, such systems are dubbed "stovepipe systems" because they consist of components that have been jammed together in a way that makes it very hard to modify them in any way.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] If integration is applied without following a structured EAI approach, point-to-point connections grow across an organization.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Dependencies are added on an impromptu basis, resulting in a complex structure that is difficult to maintain.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] This is commonly referred to as spaghetti, an allusion to the programming equivalent of spaghetti code.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] For example, the number of connections needed to have fully meshed point-to-point connections, with n points, is given by ${\tbinom {n}{2}}={\tfrac {n(n-1)}{2}}$ (see binomial coefficient).
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Thus, for ten applications to be fully integrated point-to-point, ${\tfrac {10\times 9}{2}}=45$ point-to-point connections are needed, following a quadratic growth pattern.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] However, the number of connections within organizations does not necessarily grow according to the square of the number of points.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] In general, the number of connections to any point is only limited by the number of other points in an organization, but can be significantly smaller in principle.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] EAI can also increase coupling between systems and therefore increase management overhead and costs.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] EAI is not just about sharing data between applications but also focuses on sharing both business data and business processes.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] A middleware analyst attending to EAI will often look at the system of systems.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] This section describes common design patterns for implementing EAI, including integration, access and lifetime patterns.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] These are abstract patterns and can be implemented in many different ways.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] There are many other patterns commonly used in the industry, ranging from high-level abstract design patterns to highly specific implementation patterns.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Here, the EAI system acts as the go-between or broker between multiple applications.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Whenever an interesting event occurs in an application (for instance, new information is created or a new transaction completed) an integration module in the EAI system is notified.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] The module then propagates the changes to other relevant applications.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] In this case, the EAI system acts as the overarching facade across multiple applications.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] All event calls from the 'outside world' to any of the applications are front-ended by the EAI system.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] The EAI system is configured to expose only the relevant information and interfaces of the underlying applications to the outside world, and performs all interactions with the underlying applications on behalf of the requester.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Both patterns are often used concurrently.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] The same EAI system could be keeping multiple applications in sync (mediation), while servicing requests from external users against these applications (federation).
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] EAI supports both asynchronous (fire and forget) and synchronous access patterns, the former being typical in the mediation case and the latter in the federation case.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] There are two major topologies: hub-and-spoke, and bus.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Each has its own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] In the hub-and-spoke model, the EAI system is at the center (the hub), and interacts with the applications via the spokes.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] In the bus model, the EAI system is the bus (or is implemented as a resident module in an already existing message bus or message-oriented middleware).
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Most large enterprises use zoned networks to create a layered defense against network oriented threats.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] For example, an enterprise typically has a credit card processing (PCI-compliant) zone, a non-PCI zone, a data zone, a DMZ zone to proxy external user access, and an IWZ zone to proxy internal user access.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Applications need to integrate across multiple zones.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] The **Hub and spoke** model would work better in this case.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] , message bus) or implemented as a stand-alone program (i.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] e., does not use any middleware), acting as its own middleware.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] These are programs that know how to interact with an underlying business application.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] The adapter performs one-way communication(unidirectional), performing requests from the hub against the application, and notifying the hub when an event of interest occurs in the application (a new record inserted, a transaction completed, etc.).
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Adapters can be specific to an application (e.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] g., built against the application vendor's client libraries) or specific to a class of applications (e.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] The adapter could reside in the same process space as the bus/hub or execute in a remote location and interact with the hub/bus through industry-standard protocols such as message queues, web services, or even use a proprietary protocol.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] allow adapters to be created in a vendor-neutral manner.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] To avoid every adapter having to convert data to/from every other application's formats, EAI systems usually stipulate an application-independent (or common) data format.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] The EAI system usually provides a data transformation service as well to help convert between application-specific and common formats.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] This is done in two steps: the adapter converts information from the application's format to the bus's common format.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Then, semantic transformations are applied to this (converting zip codes to city names, splitting/merging objects from one application into objects in the other applications, and so on).
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] An EAI system could be participating in multiple concurrent integration operations at any given time, each type of integration being processed by a different integration module.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Integration modules subscribe to events of specific types and process notifications that they receive when these events occur.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] that conform to the EAI system's specifications.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Currently, there are many variations of thought on what constitutes the best infrastructure, component model, and standards structure for Enterprise Application Integration.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] An independent data model based on a standard data structure, also known as a canonical data model.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] It appears that XML and the use of XML style sheets have become the *de facto* and in some cases *de jure* standard for this uniform business language.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] A connector, or agent model where each vendor, application, or interface can build a single component that can speak natively to that application and communicate with the centralized broker.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] A system model that defines the APIs, data flow and rules of engagement to the system such that components can be built to interface with it in a standardized way.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Although other approaches like connecting at the database or user-interface level have been explored, they have not been found to scale or be able to adjust.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Individual applications can publish messages to the centralized broker and subscribe to receive certain messages from that broker.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Each application only requires one connection to the broker.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] This central control approach can be extremely scalable and highly evolvable.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Enterprise Application Integration is related to middleware technologies such as message-oriented middleware (MOM), and data representation technologies such as XML or JSON.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Other EAI technologies involve using web services as part of service-oriented architecture as a means of integration.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Enterprise Application Integration tends to be data centric.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] In the near future, it will come to include content integration and business processes.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] In 2003 it was reported that 70% of all EAI projects fail.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Most of these failures are not due to the software itself or technical difficulties, but due to management issues.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Integration Consortium European Chairman Steve Craggs has outlined the seven main pitfalls undertaken by companies using EAI systems and explains solutions to these problems.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Shortage of EAI experts: EAI requires knowledge of many issues and technical aspects.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Competing standards: Within the EAI field, the paradox is that EAI standards themselves are not universal.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] EAI is a tool paradigm: EAI is not a tool, but rather a system and should be implemented as such.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Building interfaces is an art: Engineering the solution is not sufficient.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Solutions need to be negotiated with user departments to reach a common consensus on the final outcome.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] A lack of consensus on interface designs leads to excessive effort to map between various systems' data requirements.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Loss of detail: Information that seemed unimportant at an earlier stage may become crucial later.
[src:spring-framework-lib/enterprise-application-integration] Accountability: Since so many departments have many conflicting requirements, there should be clear accountability for the system's final structure.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] In software design, **inversion of control** (**IoC**) is a design principle in which custom-written portions of a computer program receive the flow of control from an external source (e.g. a framework).
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] The term "inversion" is historical: a software architecture with this design "inverts" control as compared to procedural programming.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] In procedural programming, a program's custom code calls reusable libraries to take care of generic tasks, but with inversion of control, it is the external code or framework that is in control and calls the custom code.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Inversion of control has been widely used by application development frameworks since the rise of GUI environments and continues to be used both in GUI environments and in web server application frameworks.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Inversion of control makes the framework extensible by the methods defined by the application programmer.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Event-driven programming is often implemented using IoC so that the custom code need only be concerned with the handling of events, while the event loop and dispatch of events/messages is handled by the framework or the runtime environment.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] In web server application frameworks, dispatch is usually called routing, and handlers may be called endpoints.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] The phrase "inversion of control" has separately also come to be used in the community of Java programmers to refer specifically to the patterns of dependency injection (passing services to objects that need them) that occur with "IoC containers" in Java frameworks such as the Spring Framework.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] As an example, with traditional programming, the main function of an application might make function calls into a menu library to display a list of available commands and query the user to select one.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] The library thus would return the chosen option as the value of the function call, and the main function uses this value to execute the associated command.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] This style was common in text-based interfaces.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] For example, an email client may show a screen with commands to load new mail, answer the current mail, create new mail, etc., and the program execution would block until the user presses a key to select a command.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] With inversion of control, on the other hand, the program would be written using a software framework that knows common behavioral and graphical elements, such as windowing systems, menus, controlling the mouse, and toolbars.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] The custom code "fills in the blanks" for the framework, such as supplying a table of menu items and registering a code subroutine for each item, but it is the framework that monitors the user's actions and invokes the subroutine when a menu item is selected.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] In the mail client example, the framework could follow both the keyboard and mouse inputs and call the command invoked by the user by either means and at the same time monitor the network interface to find out if new messages arrive and refresh the screen when some network activity is detected.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] The same framework could be used as the skeleton for a spreadsheet program or a text editor.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Conversely, the framework knows nothing about Web browsers, spreadsheets, or text editors; implementing their functionality takes custom code.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Inversion of control carries the strong connotation that the reusable code and the problem-specific code are developed independently even though they operate together in an application.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Callbacks, schedulers, event loops, and the template method are examples of design patterns that follow the inversion of control principle, although the term is most commonly used in the context of object-oriented programming.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Inversion of control is sometimes referred to as the "Hollywood Principle: Don't call us, we'll call you," reflecting how frameworks dictate execution flow.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] The etymology of the phrase has been traced back to 1988, but it is closely related to the concept of **program inversion** described by Michael Jackson in his Jackson Structured Programming methodology in the 1970s.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] A bottom-up parser can be seen as an inversion of a top-down parser: in the one case, the control lies with the parser, while in the other case, it lies with the receiving application.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] The phrase was further popularized in 2004 by Robert C.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Martin and Martin Fowler, the latter of whom traces the term's origins to the 1980s.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] In traditional programming, the flow of the business logic is determined by objects that are statically bound to one another.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] With inversion of control, the flow depends on the object graph that is built up during program execution.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Such a dynamic flow is made possible by object interactions that are defined through abstractions.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] This run-time binding is achieved by mechanisms such as dependency injection or a service locator.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] In IoC, the code could also be linked statically during compilation, but finding the code to execute by reading its description from external configuration instead of with a direct reference in the code itself.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] In dependency injection, a dependent object or module is coupled to the object it needs at run time.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Which particular object will satisfy the dependency during program execution typically cannot be known at compile time using static analysis.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] While described in terms of object interaction here, the principle can apply to other programming methodologies besides object-oriented programming.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] In order for the running program to bind objects to one another, the objects must possess compatible interfaces.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] For example, class `A` may delegate behavior to interface `I` which is implemented by class `B`; the program instantiates `A` and `B`, and then injects `B` into `A`.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] Web browsers implement inversion of control for DOM events in HTML.
[src:spring-framework-lib/inversion-of-control] The application developer uses `document.addEventListener()` to register a callback.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
