[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:spring-framework-lib/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] A **software framework** is software that provides reusable, generic functionality which developers can extend or customize to create complete solutions.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] It offers an abstraction layer over lower-level code and infrastructure, allowing developers to focus on implementing business logic rather than building common functionality from scratch.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] Generally, a framework is intended to enhance productivity by allowing developers to focus on satisfying business requirements rather than reimplementing generic functionality.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] Frameworks often include support programs, compilers, software development kits, code libraries, toolsets, and APIs that integrate various components within a larger software platform or environment.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] Unlike a library, where user code controls the program's control flow, a framework implements inversion of control by dictating the overall structure and calling user code at predefined extension points (e.g., through template methods or hooks).
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] Frameworks also provide default behaviours that work out-of-the-box, structured mechanisms for extensibility, and a fixed core that accepts extensions (e.g., plugins or subclasses) without direct modification.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] A framework differs from an application that can be extended—such as a web browser via an extension or a video game via a mod—in that it is intentionally incomplete scaffolding designed to be completed through its extension points while following specific architectural patterns.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] For example, a team using a web framework to develop a banking website can focus on writing banking business logic rather than handling low-level details like web request processing or state management.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] According to Pree, software frameworks consist of *frozen spots* and *hot spots*.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] *Frozen spots* define the overall architecture of a software system, that is to say its basic components and the relationships between them.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] These remain unchanged (frozen) in any instantiation of the application framework.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] *Hot spots* represent the parts where the programmers using the framework add their own code to add the functionality specific to their own project.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] The necessary functionality can be implemented by using the Template Method Pattern in which the *frozen spots* are known as invariant methods and the *hot spots* are known as variant or hook methods.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] The invariant methods in the superclass provide default behaviour while the hook methods in each subclass provide custom behaviour.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] When developing a concrete software system with a software framework, developers utilize the hot spots according to the specific needs and requirements of the system.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] Software frameworks rely on the Hollywood Principle: "Don't call us, we'll call you." This means that the user-defined classes (for example, new subclasses) receive messages from the predefined framework classes.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] Developers usually handle this by implementing superclass abstract methods.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] One potential downside of using a framework is that it adds to the size of a program, a phenomenon termed code bloat.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] This can be exacerbated by using multiple, sometimes competing, frameworks in the same codebase.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] Learning how to use a framework can be substantial.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] The intended efficiencies of using the framework may be outweighed by the cost to learn it, especially for a framework that is new to the development staff.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] However, once a framework is learned, development team speed may increase for future work.
[src:spring-framework-lib/software-framework] Some claim that the most effective frameworks evolve from re-factoring an existing solution, such as a generic one-size-fits-all framework developed by third parties for general purposes, rather than from green-field development.
